.TH TIMEDEXEC 1 "2025" "v1.0.0" "User Commands"

.SH NAME
timedexec \- run a command with CPU, memory, and wall\-clock resource limits

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B timedexec
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
.B \-\-
\fIcommand\fR [\fIargs\fR...]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B timedexec
forks a child process to run the given \fIcommand\fR and monitors it in
real time using a dedicated POSIX thread.  If the child exceeds any of
the configured resource limits it is killed with \fBSIGKILL\fR and a
summary is printed.  Resource usage (wall time, CPU time, peak RSS) is
always reported when the child finishes.

Monitoring is done by periodically reading
.B /proc/<pid>/stat
(CPU time) and
.B /proc/<pid>/status
(RSS memory).  As a belt\-and\-suspenders measure,
.BR setrlimit (2)
is also applied to the child for the CPU limit so the kernel itself will
enforce it via \fBSIGXCPU\fR even if the monitor thread is delayed.

Signals \fBSIGINT\fR and \fBSIGTERM\fR received by
.B timedexec
are forwarded to the child process.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-t " sec"
Wall\-clock (real) time limit in seconds.  The child is killed with
\fBSIGKILL\fR if it runs longer than \fIsec\fR seconds of elapsed time.
.TP
.BI \-c " sec"
CPU time limit in seconds (user + system time consumed by the child).
.TP
.BI \-m " MB"
Resident set size (RSS) memory limit in megabytes.
.TP
.BI \-i " ms"
Polling interval in milliseconds (default: \fB500\fR).  Lower values
increase responsiveness but add overhead.
.TP
.BI \-o " file"
Write the monitoring output and final summary to \fIfile\fR instead of
\fBstderr\fR.
.TP
.B \-v
Verbose mode.  Print a resource usage line on every polling interval
while the child is running.
.TP
.B \-h
Print a short help message and exit.

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
The child exited successfully with status 0.
.TP
.B N
The child exited with status \fIN\fR.
.TP
.B 124
The child was killed because the wall\-clock time limit was exceeded.
.TP
.B 125
The child was killed because the CPU time limit was exceeded.
.TP
.B 126
The child was killed because the memory (RSS) limit was exceeded.
.TP
.B 127
An internal error occurred in
.B timedexec
itself (e.g., \fBfork\fR(2) or \fBexecvp\fR(3) failure, bad arguments).

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Kill a process that runs longer than 5 seconds:
.nf
timedexec \-t 5 \-\- sleep 10
.fi
.TP
Limit CPU to 2 seconds and memory to 512 MB, with verbose output:
.nf
timedexec \-c 2 \-m 512 \-v \-\- ./heavy_computation
.fi
.TP
All limits, poll every 200 ms, log to file:
.nf
timedexec \-t 30 \-c 10 \-m 256 \-i 200 \-o run.log \-v \-\- ./server \-p 8080
.fi
.TP
Check the exit code to detect which limit was hit:
.nf
timedexec \-t 5 \-\- ./prog
case $? in
  124) echo "Killed: wall\-clock limit";;
  125) echo "Killed: CPU limit";;
  126) echo "Killed: memory limit";;
  127) echo "Internal error";;
  *)   echo "Normal exit";;
esac
.fi

.SH TECHNICAL DETAILS
.SS System Calls and Interfaces Used
.TP
.BR fork (2)
Creates the child process.
.TP
.BR execvp (3)
Replaces the child image with the target command.
.TP
.BR pthreads (7)
A monitor thread (\fBpthread_create\fR) polls
.B /proc
at regular intervals and enforces limits independently of the main thread.
.TP
.BR getopt (3)
Parses command\-line options portably.
.TP
.BR setrlimit (2)
Applied in the child for \fBRLIMIT_CPU\fR as a kernel\-enforced backstop.
.TP
.BR getrusage (2)
Collects final CPU and peak RSS statistics after the child exits.
.TP
.BR sigaction (2)
Installs signal handlers that forward \fBSIGINT\fR/\fBSIGTERM\fR to the child.
.TP
.BR clock_gettime (2)
High\-resolution monotonic clock for wall\-time measurement.
.TP
.B /proc/<pid>/stat
Parsed for user and system CPU ticks.
.TP
.B /proc/<pid>/status
Parsed for \fBVmRSS\fR (current resident set size in kB).

.SH COMPILATION
.nf
gcc \-Wall \-Wextra \-O2 \-o timedexec timedexec.c \-lpthread
.fi

.SH BUGS
.IP \(bu 4
RSS monitoring reflects only the monitored process; child sub\-processes
are not currently tracked.
.IP \(bu 4
On very short\-lived programs the monitor thread may not sample before
the process exits; the final \fBgetrusage\fR(2) stats are still accurate.

.SH AUTHOR
Written for the CS Advanced Systems Programming project.

.SH SEE ALSO
